---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Claim from '../../components/Claim.astro';
import FactTier from '../../components/FactTier.astro';
import VarnaJatiLocator from '../../components/viz/VarnaJatiLocator.astro';
import RelatedNav from '../../components/site/RelatedNav.astro';

const subgroups = [
  { en: 'Saiva Pillai', ta: 'சைவ பிள்ளை', note: 'Saivite, often temple-affiliated; concentrated in the Cauvery delta and Tondai country.' },
  { en: 'Karkatha (Kondaikatti)', ta: 'கொண்டைகட்டி வேளாளர்', note: 'Tondai-country Vellala; the "knotted-tuft" reference is to a distinctive hairstyle.' },
  { en: 'Kongu Vellala Gounder', ta: 'கொங்கு வேளாள கவுண்டர்', note: 'Western Tamil Nadu; 145-kootam structure; Gounder title — the worked-example community on this site.' },
  { en: 'Tuluva Vellalar (Mudaliar)', ta: 'துளுவ வேளாளர் / முதலியார்', note: 'Northern Tamil; Mudaliar title common; some sub-groups trace migration from Tulu Nadu (coastal Karnataka).' },
  { en: 'Saiva Pillai (Sri Lankan)', ta: 'ஈழ வேளாளர்', note: 'Jaffna-region Vellala; historically the demographic majority of northern Sri Lankan Tamils.' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Vellala — Decoded"
  description="Deep-dive on the Vellala caste-cluster: etymology, Sangam origins, sub-groups, irrigation legacy, and the contested 'noble cultivator' narrative."
>
  <main id="main-content" class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-12 sm:py-16">
    <nav class="mb-8 text-sm text-stone-500">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-stone-900 rounded focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-2" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/lineage" class="hover:text-stone-900 rounded focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">Lineage</a>
      <span class="mx-2" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span class="text-stone-700">Vellala</span>
    </nav>

    <VarnaJatiLocator highlightSlug="vellala" class="mb-6" />

    <header class="mb-10">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-emerald-700">Caste cluster · ஜாதிக் கொத்து</p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">
        <span class="block">Vellala</span>
        <span class="mt-2 block font-tamil text-3xl font-medium text-stone-700 sm:text-4xl">
          வேளாளர்
        </span>
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl text-base text-stone-600 sm:text-lg">
        The Tamil cultivator caste-cluster. A category that sweeps in several historically distinct regional sub-groups — including the Kongu Vellala Gounder — and that has been variously mapped onto the four-varna schema, with disagreement that has never really resolved.
      </p>
    </header>

    {/* Etymology */}
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Etymology
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">சொல் வரலாறு</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="prose prose-stone prose-editorial has-dropcap mt-4 max-w-none text-stone-800 sm:text-lg">
        <p>
          The most commonly cited Tamil derivation is <strong>vellam</strong> (வெள்ளம், flood / abundant water) + <strong>aanmai</strong> (ஆண்மை, mastery / governance) — "masters of water" — referencing the community's historical role in tank and well irrigation. Alternative derivations relate the word to <em>vēl</em> (வேள், chieftain) or to the Velir clans of the Sangam era.
        </p>
        <p>
          Folk etymologies are common in caste names and are usually retrospective. The "masters of water" gloss is plausible and resonant; it is also, frankly, flattering to the community. It is best read as a popular etymology with a real material referent (the documented irrigation systems) rather than a securely established linguistic origin.
          <FactTier tier="yellow" />
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Sangam origin */}
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Sangam-era origin
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">சங்க கால தோற்றம்</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="prose prose-stone mt-4 max-w-none text-stone-800 sm:text-lg">
        <p>
          <Claim tier="yellow" sources={["vellala-kaveri-origin"]}>
            The Vellala cluster is most commonly hypothesised to have originated as elite land-owning cultivators of the Kaveri delta and other wet-rice zones during and after the Sangam era, expanding subsequently into Kongu, Tondai, and Pandya country.
          </Claim>
          The Sangam corpus references <em>ulavar</em> (உழவர், ploughmen / cultivators) as a respected category, and the Velir chieftain class is well-attested. Whether the historical Velir are a direct ancestor of the modern Vellala is a separate, harder question.
        </p>
        <p>
          <Claim tier="green" sources={["vellala-tank-irrigation"]}>
            The Vellala-led tank-and-well irrigation systems are well-documented in inscriptions and medieval administrative records across the Kaveri delta, Kongu region, and Tondai country.
          </Claim>
          This is the strongest piece of evidence for the cluster's material identity — the actual hydraulic engineering, attested across centuries.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Sub-groups */}
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Sub-groups within the cluster
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">உட்பிரிவுகள்</span>
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-2 max-w-2xl text-stone-600">
        "Vellala" is a category, not a single endogamous group. These regional sub-groups have historically not intermarried freely, and several use different titles (Pillai, Mudaliar, Gounder).
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-stone-200 bg-white">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead class="bg-stone-50 text-left text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3">Sub-group</th>
              <th class="hidden px-4 py-3 sm:table-cell">Tamil</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3">Note</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-stone-200">
            {subgroups.map((s) => (
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-stone-900">{s.en}</td>
                <td class="hidden px-4 py-3 font-tamil text-stone-700 sm:table-cell">{s.ta}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-stone-700">{s.note}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Varna placement contested */}
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Varna placement — contested and historically variable
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">வர்ண நிலை</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="prose prose-stone mt-4 max-w-none text-stone-800 sm:text-lg">
        <p>
          Within the four-varna schema, the Vellala mapping is genuinely contested. Different sub-groups have at different times claimed Kshatriya status, Vaishya status, "Sat-Shudra" status, or rejected the four-varna schema entirely as a Sanskritic imposition irrelevant to Tamil society. None of these claims is securely demonstrable as the "original" position; all of them have political stakes — see the colonial-census timeline for the period when these claims were systematically codified and contested in writing.
        </p>
        <p>
          The honest answer is: the Vellala caste-cluster, like most Tamil cultivator castes, sat outside the cleanest applications of the four-varna template and was forced into one box or another by the colonial classification machinery.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Contested historiography */}
    <section class="mb-12 rounded-2xl border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 p-6">
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xl font-semibold text-amber-900">
        Contested historiography
        <FactTier tier="yellow" />
      </h2>
      <div class="prose prose-stone mt-3 max-w-none text-stone-800">
        <p>
          The dominant narrative about the Vellala — "noble cultivator, master of water, ritually respected, descended from the Sangam-era Velir chieftains" — is partly community self-representation. It is not false, but it is also not the whole picture.
        </p>
        <p>
          The same hydraulic systems that the Vellala managed were worked by labouring castes; the same kootam structure that organised the Kongu Vellala excluded outsiders from intermarriage; the same "noble cultivator" framing operated as a status claim against neighbouring communities in colonial-era enumeration disputes. The romanticised version of the Vellala story tends to centre the management role and leave the broader rural labour ecology in the background.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is not a unique problem with the Vellala. Almost every Indian caste's narrative about itself does this; the goal of this project is to flag it, not to pick a side.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Cross-links */}
    <section class="rounded-2xl border border-stone-200 bg-white p-6">
      <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-stone-900">Connected pages</h2>
      <ul class="mt-3 grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-3">
        <li>
          <a href="/lineage/kongu" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-amber-300 hover:bg-amber-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Region</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Kongu Nadu</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">The western Tamil region.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/lineage/gounder" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-amber-300 hover:bg-amber-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Title</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Gounder (கவுண்டர்)</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">Headman title used by Kongu Vellala.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/overview/varna-vs-jati" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-sky-300 hover:bg-sky-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Overview</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Varna vs Jati</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">Where Vellala sits in the larger schema.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <RelatedNav
      readNext={{
        href: '/lineage/gounder',
        title: 'Gounder',
        sub: 'The headman title carried by Kongu Vellala families.',
      }}
      related={{
        label: 'Related overview',
        items: [
          { href: '/overview/varna-vs-jati', title: 'Varna vs Jati — where Vellala sits' },
        ],
      }}
      backTo={{ href: '/lineage', label: 'Lineage hub' }}
    />
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
